WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.704
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.325 --> 00:00:06.950
BEN SCHROM: My name
is Benjamin Schrom.

00:00:06.950 --> 00:00:09.100
I'm a product manager
on the Daydream team,

00:00:09.100 --> 00:00:13.870
focused specifically on using
immersive technology like VR/AR

00:00:13.870 --> 00:00:16.450
to make learning
and teaching better.

00:00:16.450 --> 00:00:18.690
And I'm joined by two
members of our team here--

00:00:18.690 --> 00:00:21.820
Jen, who's our program manager,
fresh from the Daydream keynote

00:00:21.820 --> 00:00:25.621
just now, and Brandon, who
leads our engineering team.

00:00:25.621 --> 00:00:28.120
So we're going to share some
updates on Expeditions with you

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:30.490
today, show what we've
been up to lately,

00:00:30.490 --> 00:00:32.500
and then show you how
it's possible to make

00:00:32.500 --> 00:00:35.470
your own learning
application with VR/AR,

00:00:35.470 --> 00:00:38.740
and then offer some thoughts
about why you should do that.

00:00:38.740 --> 00:00:42.160
Now, I'd wager if you ask most
people to list the things they

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:45.490
think VR would be good for,
most people would actually

00:00:45.490 --> 00:00:48.392
put education sort of
at the top of that list.

00:00:48.392 --> 00:00:50.350
We talk about it sort of
like it seems obvious,

00:00:50.350 --> 00:00:51.391
and it is pretty obvious.

00:00:51.391 --> 00:00:55.010
It's like the first thing we
did with it here at Google.

00:00:55.010 --> 00:00:56.530
But it's not just
because VR is fun

00:00:56.530 --> 00:00:58.180
or because it makes you feel
like you're somewhere else

00:00:58.180 --> 00:01:00.070
that it's an obvious
fit for learning.

00:01:00.070 --> 00:01:02.560
At least within our team,
it's because it powerfully

00:01:02.560 --> 00:01:06.040
supports what our
values are as people

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:11.490
who are trying to enable better
learning with technology.

00:01:11.490 --> 00:01:12.710
And what are those values?

00:01:12.710 --> 00:01:14.918
Well, for us, we think that
good learning experiences

00:01:14.918 --> 00:01:17.200
should be fundamentally
immersive, interactive,

00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:19.000
and social.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.370
And we act, no surprise,
that we actually

00:01:21.370 --> 00:01:23.830
believe those same
things are the ones that

00:01:23.830 --> 00:01:25.880
characterize VR experiences.

00:01:28.465 --> 00:01:29.840
We think they
should be immersive

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:32.420
because being engaged,
interested, emotionally

00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:34.760
invested-- these are really
important contexts in which

00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:35.716
to learn.

00:01:35.716 --> 00:01:37.965
And when things are immersive,
they are less abstract.

00:01:37.965 --> 00:01:41.670
There's sort of less
cognitive load to process.

00:01:41.670 --> 00:01:43.790
We also think that they
need to be interactive

00:01:43.790 --> 00:01:46.670
because it's empowering
them agency as a user,

00:01:46.670 --> 00:01:49.730
to not feel constrained, to
be able to have a thought

00:01:49.730 --> 00:01:52.490
and see a result,
to be able to dig in

00:01:52.490 --> 00:01:56.090
deeper when you see something
that piques your interest.

00:01:56.090 --> 00:01:58.820
And they're social because
when people come together

00:01:58.820 --> 00:02:01.220
as a group with
diverse viewpoints

00:02:01.220 --> 00:02:04.350
that they discuss
and synthesize,

00:02:04.350 --> 00:02:07.350
then we learn from one another.

00:02:07.350 --> 00:02:11.959
And we end up with the sum
that's greater than the parts.

00:02:11.959 --> 00:02:13.500
And this is important
to us at Google

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:17.670
because we aren't interested in
just creating future graduates.

00:02:17.670 --> 00:02:19.710
We want to create
future creators,

00:02:19.710 --> 00:02:22.200
inventors, problem
solvers, dreamers.

00:02:25.290 --> 00:02:27.150
So that's why we
started Expeditions.

00:02:27.150 --> 00:02:30.150
We wanted to give schools
a simple, approachable, and

00:02:30.150 --> 00:02:33.150
immediately useful tool for
using VR in the classroom

00:02:33.150 --> 00:02:36.210
and creating more of those
sorts of experiences on a more

00:02:36.210 --> 00:02:37.470
regular basis.

00:02:37.470 --> 00:02:41.040
And here to talk to you a
little bit more about it is Jen.

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:43.290
JENNIFER HOLLAND: Thanks, Ben.

00:02:43.290 --> 00:02:47.130
So Expeditions was
announced two years ago,

00:02:47.130 --> 00:02:49.170
and it was our first
large-scale effort

00:02:49.170 --> 00:02:51.180
to bring VR in the classroom.

00:02:51.180 --> 00:02:55.200
And all schools needed was a
simple smartphone or tablet

00:02:55.200 --> 00:02:56.910
and a VR viewer,
and they could be

00:02:56.910 --> 00:02:59.400
teleported all over the world--

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:01.495
underwater and even to Mars.

00:03:05.250 --> 00:03:07.890
And on our team, many
of the same people

00:03:07.890 --> 00:03:11.010
that built Classroom and
G Suite for Education

00:03:11.010 --> 00:03:13.050
are the same people
that built Expeditions.

00:03:13.050 --> 00:03:16.830
And we were able to rely really
heavily on those insights

00:03:16.830 --> 00:03:18.534
that we acquired.

00:03:18.534 --> 00:03:20.700
And one of the most important
things that we learned

00:03:20.700 --> 00:03:22.950
is that you really need to
embrace the key functions

00:03:22.950 --> 00:03:24.040
of a classroom.

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:26.670
That's students
engaging, interacting,

00:03:26.670 --> 00:03:29.265
learning with each other
as well as their peers.

00:03:29.265 --> 00:03:31.140
But there are also a
couple other things that

00:03:31.140 --> 00:03:32.348
are actually really critical.

00:03:32.348 --> 00:03:34.720
One is it needs to
be so easy to use.

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:37.590
You can't rely on teachers to
go to professional development

00:03:37.590 --> 00:03:40.010
training to get
trained on your tool.

00:03:40.010 --> 00:03:42.970
Two, you need to really
make that immersion,

00:03:42.970 --> 00:03:46.800
that social connection
between teachers and students,

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:48.690
and students and students.

00:03:48.690 --> 00:03:52.770
And make making sure that
it's engaging and interacting.

00:03:52.770 --> 00:03:56.600
And you need to make sure
that your product works

00:03:56.600 --> 00:03:58.830
on multiple devices
and platforms.

00:03:58.830 --> 00:04:00.750
And that's really
important because schools

00:04:00.750 --> 00:04:02.610
have a variety of
devices, and they

00:04:02.610 --> 00:04:03.930
have a variety of platforms.

00:04:03.930 --> 00:04:06.540
And they're not just
going to pick one.

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:10.650
And you can't expect teachers
to replace their materials

00:04:10.650 --> 00:04:11.220
overnight.

00:04:11.220 --> 00:04:14.100
And so you need to make sure
your tool or your product

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:17.160
can easily fit into the
existing curriculum.

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:19.470
And that's what we
did with Expeditions.

00:04:19.470 --> 00:04:22.140
And just like
Chromebooks, we imagined

00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:25.500
that the Expedition Kits
would be a shared resource

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:28.365
between classes and schools.

00:04:33.569 --> 00:04:35.110
One of the biggest
things we realized

00:04:35.110 --> 00:04:38.200
was that most teachers
weren't actually aware of VR

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:40.010
when we first started this.

00:04:40.010 --> 00:04:44.290
And so what we decided to do
was bring Expeditions to schools

00:04:44.290 --> 00:04:47.200
through the Expeditions
Pioneer Program.

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:51.100
And what we saw was that
once teachers got a chance

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:54.370
to see VR in action
and see how Expeditions

00:04:54.370 --> 00:04:57.940
could transform their classroom,
they were immediately hooked.

00:04:57.940 --> 00:05:00.820
And so the first year,
we took Expeditions

00:05:00.820 --> 00:05:03.580
to over a million
students in 11 countries.

00:05:03.580 --> 00:05:06.340
And we got incredible feedback,
particularly from teachers

00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:07.330
in the UK.

00:05:07.330 --> 00:05:10.360
So this past year we
actually went back to the UK,

00:05:10.360 --> 00:05:12.460
and we just wrapped
up our program there.

00:05:12.460 --> 00:05:16.570
And we took another
million students in the UK

00:05:16.570 --> 00:05:17.530
on an Expedition.

00:05:17.530 --> 00:05:19.990
And that's one in
about every eight

00:05:19.990 --> 00:05:22.925
primary and secondary
students in all of the UK.

00:05:25.820 --> 00:05:27.740
So that brings our
total number of students

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:30.560
that I've gone on and used
Expeditions to over two million

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:31.650
in the last two years.

00:05:34.460 --> 00:05:36.380
And even after
Expeditions has been

00:05:36.380 --> 00:05:39.290
used for weeks or
months or years,

00:05:39.290 --> 00:05:41.450
we still get the
same teacher feedback

00:05:41.450 --> 00:05:43.920
like this each and every day.

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:46.640
And so it's not just
the novelty of VR.

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:51.080
Clearly something is
working in the classroom.

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:53.210
And even more
importantly, we've heard

00:05:53.210 --> 00:05:56.360
from thousands of students
from around the world who

00:05:56.360 --> 00:05:57.710
have sent us personal letters.

00:05:57.710 --> 00:06:01.460
And actually, these are just
the ones we got last week.

00:06:01.460 --> 00:06:02.480
So you can see.

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:06.170
And I want to share one of them
with you because it's really

00:06:06.170 --> 00:06:08.240
too precious not to share.

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:09.410
So this is from Lozen.

00:06:09.410 --> 00:06:12.800
He's a student in the UK,
and he sent us this letter.

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:14.720
He said, "The whole
experience has

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:17.510
made me even more keen
to become a doctor

00:06:17.510 --> 00:06:19.820
and study the human
body thoroughly.

00:06:19.820 --> 00:06:23.660
The technology I used helped
me understand complex subjects

00:06:23.660 --> 00:06:24.920
easily.

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:28.160
The solar system trip was
incredibly fascinating.

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:30.350
I did not feel myself
sitting in class.

00:06:30.350 --> 00:06:34.660
Instead, I felt like Tim Peake
orbiting the solar system.

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:36.590
Now I'm not sure
whether I should

00:06:36.590 --> 00:06:39.170
be a doctor or an astronaut.

00:06:39.170 --> 00:06:41.300
I'm quite confused
at this moment.

00:06:41.300 --> 00:06:44.060
My mom says I should watch more
of these Google Expeditions

00:06:44.060 --> 00:06:45.590
before I make up my mind.

00:06:45.590 --> 00:06:49.127
And for once, I think
I'll listen to her."

00:06:49.127 --> 00:06:51.881
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:51.881 --> 00:06:54.320
And yes, Lozen, we
agree with your mom.

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:57.068
You should probably go on
more Google Expeditions.

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:02.006
So things are clearly
working, and there's

00:07:02.006 --> 00:07:03.630
quite a bit of momentum
that's actually

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:05.610
happening in the ecosystem.

00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:09.120
We're seeing hundreds of
partners create Expeditions--

00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:11.370
everything from traditional
education partners

00:07:11.370 --> 00:07:14.580
like HMH to
nontraditional partners.

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:17.190
And we're working with museums
and cultural institutions

00:07:17.190 --> 00:07:20.310
to create these Expeditions,
and we have a growing library

00:07:20.310 --> 00:07:23.130
of over 600 tours.

00:07:23.130 --> 00:07:25.410
We've also worked with
many hardware partners

00:07:25.410 --> 00:07:27.330
to create certified
Expedition Kits.

00:07:27.330 --> 00:07:29.850
So that all the hardware
that class of 30

00:07:29.850 --> 00:07:32.550
would actually need
to take an Expedition.

00:07:32.550 --> 00:07:35.640
And Best Buy Education was
one of our first partners

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:39.630
that we worked with last year
to launch an Expeditions Kit.

00:07:39.630 --> 00:07:42.000
And we've now worked with
several other partners

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.250
around the globe to ensure
that schools actually

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:48.370
have certified kits to use.

00:07:48.370 --> 00:07:50.550
We've also worked really
closely with teachers

00:07:50.550 --> 00:07:52.290
to create supporting
lesson plans, which

00:07:52.290 --> 00:07:54.930
is really important because,
as I mentioned earlier,

00:07:54.930 --> 00:07:56.670
the lessons need
to be incorporated

00:07:56.670 --> 00:07:59.250
into the actual curriculum
so that teachers

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:01.150
can use it seamlessly.

00:08:01.150 --> 00:08:03.750
And so we partnered with
Tes to upload these lessons.

00:08:03.750 --> 00:08:05.640
And Tes is a global platform.

00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:07.140
It has over eight
million teachers

00:08:07.140 --> 00:08:10.350
that are sharing and
learning with each other

00:08:10.350 --> 00:08:13.260
and their lesson materials.

00:08:13.260 --> 00:08:15.150
And what's really cool
is that we're also

00:08:15.150 --> 00:08:17.820
seeing Expeditions used
outside of the classroom,

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:20.550
and that's something that we
didn't initially anticipate.

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:22.380
We're seeing government
organizations.

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:23.640
We're seeing nonprofits.

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:28.860
And we're seeing businesses
start to use Expeditions.

00:08:28.860 --> 00:08:31.050
So let's just take a
look at one example.

00:08:31.050 --> 00:08:33.809
And what you see on the screen
is actually our Coral Bleaching

00:08:33.809 --> 00:08:35.340
Expedition.

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:38.309
So it's basically highlighting
the coral bleaching

00:08:38.309 --> 00:08:40.890
event that took place in 2014.

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:43.049
And Michael, who is a
sixth grade earth science

00:08:43.049 --> 00:08:48.360
teacher in New Jersey
used this Expedition

00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:50.910
to explain the impact
that climate change was

00:08:50.910 --> 00:08:53.394
happening to his students.

00:08:53.394 --> 00:08:55.560
And they were able to go
underwater and actually see

00:08:55.560 --> 00:08:57.690
the coral bleaching event.

00:08:57.690 --> 00:09:00.090
And when talking to Michael
about the experience,

00:09:00.090 --> 00:09:02.340
he highlighted that
Expedition continues

00:09:02.340 --> 00:09:05.127
to add another layer
of authenticity

00:09:05.127 --> 00:09:06.960
to the learning in the
classroom by using it

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:09.780
effectively and seamlessly
and integrating it

00:09:09.780 --> 00:09:13.420
into the curriculum.

00:09:13.420 --> 00:09:15.850
And what amazed me, though,
about this expedition

00:09:15.850 --> 00:09:18.070
in particular was
that it was used

00:09:18.070 --> 00:09:22.210
at COP21, which
happened in Paris

00:09:22.210 --> 00:09:24.670
and it was the UN climate
change conference.

00:09:24.670 --> 00:09:27.400
And I was actually
fortunate enough to attend.

00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:29.830
And there was a
presentation with about 150

00:09:29.830 --> 00:09:30.730
different scientists.

00:09:30.730 --> 00:09:32.800
And it was a big panel.

00:09:32.800 --> 00:09:35.080
and what was a one-way
dialogue between the panel

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:37.750
and the audience
became really lively

00:09:37.750 --> 00:09:40.570
when a scientist actually
took an Expeditions Kit

00:09:40.570 --> 00:09:43.420
and started passing it
out to the audience.

00:09:43.420 --> 00:09:45.550
Everyone started going on
this expedition together

00:09:45.550 --> 00:09:48.610
and actually could observe the
big coral bleaching event that

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:51.190
happened in Hawaii in 2014.

00:09:51.190 --> 00:09:54.760
And the whole room was
transformed instantly.

00:09:54.760 --> 00:09:56.500
So we're seeing some
of these examples

00:09:56.500 --> 00:09:58.880
occur rather frequently.

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:01.785
And it's really exciting for
us to see not only Expeditions

00:10:01.785 --> 00:10:03.160
is used in the
classroom, but how

00:10:03.160 --> 00:10:05.980
it's used outside of the
classroom over the past two

00:10:05.980 --> 00:10:08.410
years.

00:10:08.410 --> 00:10:10.650
So what's next with Expeditions?

00:10:10.650 --> 00:10:13.980
One of the most important things
that we value as an education

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:17.070
product team is listening
to teachers and students.

00:10:17.070 --> 00:10:18.990
We take feedback
really seriously,

00:10:18.990 --> 00:10:21.810
and we actually read every
single piece of feedback

00:10:21.810 --> 00:10:22.800
that we receive.

00:10:22.800 --> 00:10:26.130
And I kid you not, because my
team is the one that does it.

00:10:26.130 --> 00:10:29.850
So we're actually working to
address some of the top feature

00:10:29.850 --> 00:10:32.490
requests that we've gotten
from teachers and students,

00:10:32.490 --> 00:10:36.420
and now we're going to take
a look at a sneak peek.

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:39.360
So with over 600
tours available,

00:10:39.360 --> 00:10:42.030
we know it can be a bit
challenging for teachers

00:10:42.030 --> 00:10:47.490
to actually find the Expeditions
that we're looking for.

00:10:47.490 --> 00:10:52.190
So rolling out soon, you'll see
a new UI in the Expeditions app

00:10:52.190 --> 00:10:55.820
that will allow you to see a
set of featured Expeditions.

00:10:55.820 --> 00:10:59.442
You'll be able to search
by specific categories.

00:10:59.442 --> 00:11:00.900
And we've also
improved the search.

00:11:00.900 --> 00:11:03.740
So it'll make browsing a lot
easier to find the Expeditions

00:11:03.740 --> 00:11:06.410
that you want.

00:11:06.410 --> 00:11:07.910
And the other really
important thing

00:11:07.910 --> 00:11:09.930
is that the UI is
really responsive.

00:11:09.930 --> 00:11:11.840
And it works on a
tablet or a phone.

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:15.110
So we know if you're in Magic
Window mode or full screen mode

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:16.970
with a tablet, it
will work great.

00:11:16.970 --> 00:11:20.910
Or if you're on your mobile
device, it will work fine.

00:11:20.910 --> 00:11:23.490
And so now, I'm going
to turn it over to Ben.

00:11:23.490 --> 00:11:24.980
BEN SCHROM: Thanks, Jen.

00:11:24.980 --> 00:11:27.500
We've also heard from teachers
that they want more tools

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:30.440
to explain and highlight the
things within Expedition scenes

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:32.520
and environments.

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:36.110
So we'll be bringing this
new sort of Annotations tool

00:11:36.110 --> 00:11:38.130
that lets you draw right
on top of Expeditions.

00:11:38.130 --> 00:11:40.660
And we think this is going
be really, really useful.

00:11:40.660 --> 00:11:42.290
If you think of
the number of times

00:11:42.290 --> 00:11:44.900
when you're watching a sports
commentator use a telestrator

00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:48.470
to illustrate a particularly
interesting play in a game,

00:11:48.470 --> 00:11:50.630
it's exactly the
same thing here.

00:11:50.630 --> 00:11:53.630
And the way this works is a guy
can draw something on the scene

00:11:53.630 --> 00:11:56.360
with their finger or a
stylus, like here sort

00:11:56.360 --> 00:12:00.410
of pointing out where a new
set of solar panels might go.

00:12:00.410 --> 00:12:03.410
And then each of the
connected explorers,

00:12:03.410 --> 00:12:07.162
they see that same thing
reflected on there's as well.

00:12:07.162 --> 00:12:08.892
There you go.

00:12:08.892 --> 00:12:09.600
It's really cool.

00:12:12.290 --> 00:12:14.910
And now for the number
one most requested

00:12:14.910 --> 00:12:17.980
feature of all-- the ability
to explore on your own.

00:12:17.980 --> 00:12:21.360
Now we see firsthand each day
how powerful a teaching tool

00:12:21.360 --> 00:12:24.345
Expeditions can be when used
in a classroom of 30 students.

