00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:16.840
So VR is amazing at making
you feel like you're somewhere

00:15:16.840 --> 00:15:18.934
else, like you've been
transported to a new place.

00:15:18.934 --> 00:15:21.100
But we've also heard from
many students and teachers

00:15:21.100 --> 00:15:23.410
that they want to interact
more with things or objects

00:15:23.410 --> 00:15:25.700
that you might find
in those places.

00:15:25.700 --> 00:15:27.400
It was actually one
of the first things

00:15:27.400 --> 00:15:30.352
that struck us when
watching Expeditions VR used

00:15:30.352 --> 00:15:31.060
in the classroom.

00:15:31.060 --> 00:15:33.880
It was sort of the fact
that things in VR scenes

00:15:33.880 --> 00:15:35.415
had a physical placement.

00:15:35.415 --> 00:15:36.790
And that actually
changed the way

00:15:36.790 --> 00:15:38.980
that students recalled
and talked about them.

00:15:38.980 --> 00:15:42.240
Like a student that would see
an Expedition about a shark,

00:15:42.240 --> 00:15:44.350
they'd actually point to
the place in the scene

00:15:44.350 --> 00:15:45.760
where they saw that shark.

00:15:45.760 --> 00:15:47.910
It became fixed in
their spatial memory,

00:15:47.910 --> 00:15:51.820
not in this sort of
textbook on a desk.

00:15:51.820 --> 00:15:54.480
And there may very well be
something else going on here.

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:56.980
There's this idea that's really
popular in cognitive science

00:15:56.980 --> 00:15:59.470
circles right now called
embodied cognition.

00:15:59.470 --> 00:16:01.630
And basically that
theory is that our bodies

00:16:01.630 --> 00:16:03.880
play a much bigger
role in how we think,

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:09.066
learn, and remember than we've
generally thought in the past.

00:16:09.066 --> 00:16:11.440
So the theory is that when we
move around and look around

00:16:11.440 --> 00:16:13.830
and see things
presented in AR or VR,

00:16:13.830 --> 00:16:16.300
that can tap into some
very powerful capabilities

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:18.430
of our bodies plus our minds.

00:16:21.590 --> 00:16:25.250
So Tango is the technology that
allows us to do that with AR.

00:16:25.250 --> 00:16:28.280
And we've combined the live,
social, teacher-curated

00:16:28.280 --> 00:16:30.860
capabilities of
Google Expeditions

00:16:30.860 --> 00:16:34.310
with the power of Tango
to augment the environment

00:16:34.310 --> 00:16:38.060
with virtual objects
and animations.

00:16:38.060 --> 00:16:40.550
Tango uses sophisticated
computer vision combined

00:16:40.550 --> 00:16:42.620
with some simple
sensors and a smartphone

00:16:42.620 --> 00:16:44.995
very much like the ones that
you all have in your pockets

00:16:44.995 --> 00:16:48.800
right now to sense the depth and
dimensions of the environment

00:16:48.800 --> 00:16:51.790
that you hold that phone up to.

00:16:51.790 --> 00:16:53.540
So what does this sort
of mean in practice

00:16:53.540 --> 00:16:54.980
in terms of how a
teacher would do it?

00:16:54.980 --> 00:16:56.660
Well, it makes it
possible for a teacher

00:16:56.660 --> 00:16:58.667
to sort of digitally
map their classroom

00:16:58.667 --> 00:17:00.500
and place digital objects
in them as if they

00:17:00.500 --> 00:17:02.510
existed in that space for real.

00:17:02.510 --> 00:17:05.569
And because Tango creates that
canonical sort of digital map,

00:17:05.569 --> 00:17:08.960
the objects placed in this space
are persistent across sessions,

00:17:08.960 --> 00:17:10.579
can be shared with
other devices,

00:17:10.579 --> 00:17:12.109
and allow for
students and teachers

00:17:12.109 --> 00:17:15.589
to share a common view of that.

00:17:15.589 --> 00:17:17.359
And that's one of
the key things that

00:17:17.359 --> 00:17:20.000
makes Tango a unique and
really, really powerful thing

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:21.470
in the classroom.

00:17:21.470 --> 00:17:23.329
AR isn't new in the classroom.

00:17:23.329 --> 00:17:26.150
There's lots of actually really
awesome learning applications

00:17:26.150 --> 00:17:28.670
that use device
cameras on a tablet

00:17:28.670 --> 00:17:31.130
to do pass through in order
to show digital objects.

00:17:31.130 --> 00:17:34.840
But those cameras see the world
as a flat, 2D environment,

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:37.544
and they can't create that sort
of shared social experience

00:17:37.544 --> 00:17:38.960
where a classroom
can collectively

00:17:38.960 --> 00:17:41.360
stand in front of an object
and talk about it like it

00:17:41.360 --> 00:17:42.980
was right there in the room.

00:17:42.980 --> 00:17:45.260
And we've also given
teachers similar controls

00:17:45.260 --> 00:17:48.350
that they have to those
in Exhibitions VR,

00:17:48.350 --> 00:17:51.050
allowing them to point
things out, change the object

00:17:51.050 --> 00:17:54.520
and control the
pace of the class.

00:17:54.520 --> 00:17:57.110
And it's been really fun
to sort of grant teachers

00:17:57.110 --> 00:18:00.380
this new superpower
to magically go deeper

00:18:00.380 --> 00:18:02.450
into any subject
in the classroom.

00:18:02.450 --> 00:18:04.970
And instead of, or maybe
more importantly in addition

00:18:04.970 --> 00:18:08.360
to the traditional
content used in schools,

00:18:08.360 --> 00:18:11.780
AR can place inaccessible things
right in front of the student.

00:18:11.780 --> 00:18:15.350
So we've seen it
encourage more curiosity,

00:18:15.350 --> 00:18:18.560
engender more questions and
conversation among teachers

00:18:18.560 --> 00:18:20.510
and students, and
we think it can

00:18:20.510 --> 00:18:23.030
serve is a really, really
powerful complement

00:18:23.030 --> 00:18:25.190
to VR experiences as well.

00:18:25.190 --> 00:18:27.170
VR takes you like
anywhere in the world,

00:18:27.170 --> 00:18:30.747
and AR brings anything
in the world to you.

