00:23:53.250 --> 00:23:56.150
So first off, I want to talk
about Expeditions and its two

00:23:56.150 --> 00:23:58.880
fundamental features.

00:23:58.880 --> 00:24:01.550
First, Expeditions is immersive.

00:24:01.550 --> 00:24:04.391
We use 360 imagery to surround
the students and the subject

00:24:04.391 --> 00:24:04.890
matter.

00:24:07.410 --> 00:24:10.920
Second, it provides a
co-located guided experience

00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:13.830
that allows teachers
to control and augment

00:24:13.830 --> 00:24:15.807
the experiences they
deem appropriate.

00:24:18.660 --> 00:24:20.410
So first, let's talk
about the easiest way

00:24:20.410 --> 00:24:23.230
to get 360 imagery into
your own application that

00:24:23.230 --> 00:24:25.660
can be viewable in
Cardboard or Daydream

00:24:25.660 --> 00:24:27.270
or even outside of a VR viewer.

00:24:27.270 --> 00:24:29.770
First, you need to start with
something like the RICOH THETA

00:24:29.770 --> 00:24:32.320
camera or Cardboard camera
that works on Android and iOS

00:24:32.320 --> 00:24:34.810
to capture your imagery.

00:24:34.810 --> 00:24:37.580
Once you have your
360 content available,

00:24:37.580 --> 00:24:40.000
one of the easiest
ways to actually make

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:41.590
this viewable in
your application

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:43.930
is to use something
called VR view.

00:24:43.930 --> 00:24:45.730
Now, VR view is a
drop-in component

00:24:45.730 --> 00:24:48.880
for viewing 360
photos and video.

00:24:48.880 --> 00:24:50.980
And let me walk you through
a quick sample on how

00:24:50.980 --> 00:24:52.990
to do this on Android,
but be aware this is also

00:24:52.990 --> 00:24:55.410
available on iOS
and the web as well.

00:24:58.190 --> 00:25:01.690
So step one is to add the VR
view dependency to your gradle

00:25:01.690 --> 00:25:05.750
build file if
you're using gradle.

00:25:05.750 --> 00:25:08.750
Next step is to actually
add the VR panorama view

00:25:08.750 --> 00:25:09.480
to your layout.

00:25:12.520 --> 00:25:16.210
And then finally, you simply
take your VR panorama view

00:25:16.210 --> 00:25:19.970
and you use that to load
and display your image.

00:25:19.970 --> 00:25:24.910
And almost like magic, it's now
viewable in your application.

00:25:24.910 --> 00:25:28.396
And it not only is viewable
in your application in VR,

00:25:28.396 --> 00:25:29.770
you can also view
it in something

00:25:29.770 --> 00:25:31.240
that we call Magic
Window mode that

00:25:31.240 --> 00:25:33.085
allows you to view it
outside of a viewer

00:25:33.085 --> 00:25:34.210
and move your phone around.

00:25:34.210 --> 00:25:36.772
Now I realize that I'm going
over this very, very quickly,

00:25:36.772 --> 00:25:38.980
but I'm just trying to give
everyone a quick overview

00:25:38.980 --> 00:25:42.220
of all these tools.

00:25:42.220 --> 00:25:47.560
So next up, how can you enable
a co-located guided experience?

00:25:47.560 --> 00:25:49.180
It's actually really
straightforward

00:25:49.180 --> 00:25:50.680
with the Nearby API.

00:25:50.680 --> 00:25:53.320
Let me quickly walk you through
on how to do it on Android,

00:25:53.320 --> 00:25:55.030
but this is available
on iOS as well.

00:25:57.650 --> 00:26:01.940
First up for writing the Nearby
API is, just as with VR viewer,

00:26:01.940 --> 00:26:07.430
is you add the dependency
to your gradle build file.

00:26:07.430 --> 00:26:08.930
Then what you want
to do is you want

00:26:08.930 --> 00:26:10.209
to create a message listener.

00:26:10.209 --> 00:26:11.750
And now this message
listener is what

00:26:11.750 --> 00:26:15.050
you use to actually receive
and process your messages.

00:26:15.050 --> 00:26:16.867
So you create your
message listener--

00:26:20.210 --> 00:26:22.560
create your message listener--

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:24.570
and then once you
have that listener,

00:26:24.570 --> 00:26:27.180
then you subscribe that
against the Nearby API.

00:26:27.180 --> 00:26:28.510
Pretty simple.

00:26:28.510 --> 00:26:30.510
Now once you actually
have your application that

00:26:30.510 --> 00:26:33.540
can listen to and receive
and process your messages,

00:26:33.540 --> 00:26:35.580
then you can have your
application actually

00:26:35.580 --> 00:26:37.215
publish these messages
out to clients.

00:26:40.940 --> 00:26:42.837
Now, again, I went over
this pretty quickly,

00:26:42.837 --> 00:26:44.420
but if you want to
learn more about VR

00:26:44.420 --> 00:26:46.642
view or the Nearby API,
here a couple of resources

00:26:46.642 --> 00:26:47.600
that you can check out.

00:26:52.190 --> 00:26:54.260
360 photos are great.

00:26:54.260 --> 00:26:56.540
They are simple and
easy to add to your app,

00:26:56.540 --> 00:26:58.370
but they're frankly
pretty limiting

00:26:58.370 --> 00:27:01.310
because they restrict you to
a certain type of content.

00:27:01.310 --> 00:27:03.470
As you start to
prepare experiences,

00:27:03.470 --> 00:27:05.210
say for our upcoming
standalone headset

00:27:05.210 --> 00:27:07.050
that we announced in
the keynote yesterday,

00:27:07.050 --> 00:27:10.370
you're going to want something
that's more flexible and more

00:27:10.370 --> 00:27:10.954
powerful.

00:27:10.954 --> 00:27:12.620
So what are your
options around building

00:27:12.620 --> 00:27:16.430
more advanced experiences
without getting your hands

00:27:16.430 --> 00:27:20.630
dirty with OpenGL or similar?

00:27:20.630 --> 00:27:22.370
Enter WebVR.

00:27:22.370 --> 00:27:26.080
Google has been a strong force
behind the WebVR standard,

00:27:26.080 --> 00:27:29.750
and today it is fully supported
in Chrome for Android, Firefox,

00:27:29.750 --> 00:27:31.910
Oculus, and Samsung browsers.

00:27:31.910 --> 00:27:35.420
That's all great, but what about
building your own experiences

00:27:35.420 --> 00:27:39.110
that use web technologies?

00:27:39.110 --> 00:27:40.920
What I want to talk
about is A-Frame.

00:27:40.920 --> 00:27:43.430
A-Frame is a web framework
for building virtual reality

00:27:43.430 --> 00:27:44.930
experiences.

00:27:44.930 --> 00:27:46.640
Now this actually
isn't a Google product,

00:27:46.640 --> 00:27:49.160
but I want to talk about it
because it's one of the easiest

00:27:49.160 --> 00:27:51.830
ways that I've personally found
to build VR experiences that

00:27:51.830 --> 00:27:54.690
target the web.

00:27:54.690 --> 00:27:56.910
So for instance, let's take
a look at the 360 photo

00:27:56.910 --> 00:28:00.320
I showed you earlier
in the VR view example,

00:28:00.320 --> 00:28:03.264
and let's say we wanted to add
a 2D image overlay on top of it.

00:28:03.264 --> 00:28:05.430
This is actually something
that's pretty non-trivial

00:28:05.430 --> 00:28:06.330
to do with VR view.

00:28:09.750 --> 00:28:11.310
What you can see
here in the sample--

00:28:11.310 --> 00:28:14.640
and this is actually a complete
sample on how to do this--

00:28:14.640 --> 00:28:19.410
it's very easy to add
our 360 photo and then

00:28:19.410 --> 00:28:25.170
our 2D image overlay and a
very concise amount of HTML.

00:28:25.170 --> 00:28:27.390
And this should also look
very syntactically familiar

00:28:27.390 --> 00:28:31.940
for those of you with web
development experience.

00:28:31.940 --> 00:28:36.640
And then here is this example
running in Chrome for Android.

00:28:36.640 --> 00:28:37.140
Amazing.

00:28:39.960 --> 00:28:42.270
Now I'm going to try to
talk about a slightly more

00:28:42.270 --> 00:28:43.900
complex example.

00:28:43.900 --> 00:28:46.410
Now, when I was in
school, I struggled a lot

00:28:46.410 --> 00:28:48.930
with the concept of
imaginary numbers.

00:28:48.930 --> 00:28:51.597
I mean, for one, the name
is ridiculous, right?

00:28:51.597 --> 00:28:52.680
They're imaginary numbers.

00:28:52.680 --> 00:28:55.170
They're not even real.

00:28:55.170 --> 00:28:57.900
But besides the fact
I think that the name

00:28:57.900 --> 00:29:00.630
choice of imaginary
numbers is really poor,

00:29:00.630 --> 00:29:03.780
I remember the concept
to be really intimidating

00:29:03.780 --> 00:29:06.531
because it wasn't grounded
in anything tangible.

00:29:06.531 --> 00:29:08.280
To help illustrate
what I mean, let's take

00:29:08.280 --> 00:29:11.350
a look at this parabola,
x squared plus 1.

00:29:11.350 --> 00:29:13.110
Now the fundamental
theorem of algebra

00:29:13.110 --> 00:29:14.550
actually states
that there should

00:29:14.550 --> 00:29:17.130
be a value for x that
causes this parabola

00:29:17.130 --> 00:29:20.260
to cross the x-axis, but
we aren't seeing that here.

00:29:20.260 --> 00:29:23.384
So what are we missing?

00:29:23.384 --> 00:29:24.800
Well, the trick
here is that there

00:29:24.800 --> 00:29:28.970
is a value for x that causes a
parabola to cross the x-axis,

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:30.935
but it requires us to
use imaginary numbers.

00:29:34.300 --> 00:29:36.760
And one of the reasons
this example of applying

00:29:36.760 --> 00:29:39.700
imaginary numbers
seems so inaccessible

00:29:39.700 --> 00:29:41.339
is because educators
have largely

00:29:41.339 --> 00:29:43.630
been limited to conveying
information like this on a 2D

00:29:43.630 --> 00:29:46.070
plane, like a piece of paper.

00:29:46.070 --> 00:29:47.980
But just as we represent
positive numbers

00:29:47.980 --> 00:29:52.180
on the number line in one
direction and negative numbers

00:29:52.180 --> 00:29:55.240
in the other direction,
we can actually

00:29:55.240 --> 00:29:58.930
think of imaginary numbers
as just another dimension.

00:29:58.930 --> 00:30:02.130
When we represent our
parabola in 3D space,

00:30:02.130 --> 00:30:03.670
our applied use of
imaginary numbers

00:30:03.670 --> 00:30:04.840
seems a lot more obvious.

00:30:04.840 --> 00:30:07.300
You can clearly see that
our parabola intersects

00:30:07.300 --> 00:30:08.650
with the x-axis, right?

00:30:08.650 --> 00:30:10.370
It's obvious.

00:30:10.370 --> 00:30:12.370
Well actually, it's
probably not obvious to you.

00:30:12.370 --> 00:30:14.320
And if you're feeling
completely lost, great.

00:30:14.320 --> 00:30:15.280
That's my point.

00:30:15.280 --> 00:30:18.490
I'm trying to explain all
this using traditional 2D

00:30:18.490 --> 00:30:19.480
presentation tools.

00:30:22.210 --> 00:30:26.380
Now imagine if you could enable
students to explore concepts

00:30:26.380 --> 00:30:28.480
like imaginary numbers in VR.

00:30:28.480 --> 00:30:30.790
What's amazing here is
that someone has actually

00:30:30.790 --> 00:30:33.310
already built a graphing
calculator application called

00:30:33.310 --> 00:30:36.340
MathWorld VR using A-Frame.

00:30:36.340 --> 00:30:38.680
Also, not only is this
tool available today,

00:30:38.680 --> 00:30:40.460
but it's completely open source.

00:30:40.460 --> 00:30:43.180
So if you want to take a look
at a more advanced example

00:30:43.180 --> 00:30:45.640
of using A-Frame
or targeting WebVR,

00:30:45.640 --> 00:30:48.340
this is a great place to start.

00:30:48.340 --> 00:30:51.100
And if you want to learn more
about A-Frame or MathWorld VR,

00:30:51.100 --> 00:30:52.350
you can check out these links.

00:30:55.345 --> 00:30:57.220
So everything I've shown
you up to this point

00:30:57.220 --> 00:31:01.510
has only enabled VR, and I
haven't talked about AR at all.

00:31:01.510 --> 00:31:04.480
Google is pushing toward
a web AR standard.

00:31:04.480 --> 00:31:06.790
But today, one of the
best tools for building

00:31:06.790 --> 00:31:09.940
AR experiences such as
our Expeditions AR app

00:31:09.940 --> 00:31:12.390
that you can see in
the Sandbox next door,

00:31:12.390 --> 00:31:13.840
is with something called Unity.

00:31:13.840 --> 00:31:16.930
Now if you've been building
3D games or VR content,

00:31:16.930 --> 00:31:19.840
it's very likely
you've heard of Unity.

00:31:19.840 --> 00:31:22.600
If you're new to this space,
there's a good chance maybe

00:31:22.600 --> 00:31:25.141
you aren't familiar with Unity
or haven't heard of it at all.

00:31:25.141 --> 00:31:25.840
And that's OK.

00:31:25.840 --> 00:31:29.560
Unity has been historically very
popular for building mobile 3D

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:34.690
games, but the same features
that have empowered developers

00:31:34.690 --> 00:31:36.640
to create amazing
games actually also

00:31:36.640 --> 00:31:39.910
apply really well to AR and VR.

00:31:39.910 --> 00:31:42.370
So this is why we build
Expeditions AR using Unity.

00:31:42.370 --> 00:31:45.670
Because, one, it provides
really robust support

00:31:45.670 --> 00:31:48.490
for importing and
manipulating 3D objects.

00:31:48.490 --> 00:31:50.140
It provides a
multiplayer API that

00:31:50.140 --> 00:31:52.300
works with peer-to-peer
connections, which

00:31:52.300 --> 00:31:55.449
is conducive to our traditional
co-located student-teacher

00:31:55.449 --> 00:31:57.490
classroom set up where an
internet connection may

00:31:57.490 --> 00:31:58.960
be unavailable.

00:31:58.960 --> 00:32:02.320
And most importantly, it
provides simple integration

00:32:02.320 --> 00:32:03.310
with Tango.

00:32:03.310 --> 00:32:06.160
And Tango is at the core
of Google's AR tracking

00:32:06.160 --> 00:32:07.470
capabilities.

00:32:07.470 --> 00:32:09.770
Now to provide slightly
more depth on this topic--

00:32:09.770 --> 00:32:11.270
and if you've been
paying attention,

00:32:11.270 --> 00:32:14.110
you might realize that's
a pun, though a bad one--

00:32:14.110 --> 00:32:16.260
let's talk about the three
key features of Tango.

00:32:16.260 --> 00:32:20.690
So first, Tango provides
our position in 3D space.

00:32:20.690 --> 00:32:22.660
So we know where our
device is looking

00:32:22.660 --> 00:32:23.740
and where it is located.

00:32:23.740 --> 00:32:27.520
And this is what allows
students to walk around the room

00:32:27.520 --> 00:32:32.170
and see objects from different
perspectives and distances.

00:32:32.170 --> 00:32:35.090
It also provides
surface detection.

00:32:39.810 --> 00:32:42.260
So we know a floor is a
floor and a desk is a desk.

00:32:42.260 --> 00:32:44.060
And this is what allows
us to place objects

00:32:44.060 --> 00:32:49.940
relative to our physical
space and allow teachers

00:32:49.940 --> 00:32:52.160
to place objects on
tables just as they would

00:32:52.160 --> 00:32:55.370
traditional classroom materials.

00:32:55.370 --> 00:32:57.260
And then, finally,
Tango does all of this

00:32:57.260 --> 00:32:58.940
by giving us a
global understanding

00:32:58.940 --> 00:33:00.750
of our position in space.

00:33:00.750 --> 00:33:02.780
So when we leave the
classroom and come back,

00:33:02.780 --> 00:33:03.680
the objects remain.

00:33:06.816 --> 00:33:08.740
Now if you want to
learn more about Unity

00:33:08.740 --> 00:33:11.554
for Daydream or Cardboard
or Tango integration,

00:33:11.554 --> 00:33:12.970
you can check out
these resources.

00:33:12.970 --> 00:33:15.551
I realize I went
over this very fast,

00:33:15.551 --> 00:33:17.050
but hopefully they
gave you somewhat

00:33:17.050 --> 00:33:18.520
of a broad understanding
of some of the tools

00:33:18.520 --> 00:33:21.010
available that will allow you
to build your own AR and VR

00:33:21.010 --> 00:33:21.980
experiences.

00:33:21.980 --> 00:33:22.480
All right.

00:33:22.480 --> 00:33:24.214
Let me hand you back to Ben.

00:33:24.214 --> 00:33:25.380
BEN SCHROM: Thanks, Brandon.

00:33:29.500 --> 00:33:31.970
Why are we so excited
to have you guys build

00:33:31.970 --> 00:33:34.660
AR and VR learning
experiences, and why do we

00:33:34.660 --> 00:33:37.450
think it's like almost
an urgent thing?

00:33:37.450 --> 00:33:40.690
So sort of perfectly
encapsulated in this quote

00:33:40.690 --> 00:33:43.135
from one of my heroes,
Seymour Papert.

00:33:43.135 --> 00:33:44.510
Does anybody know
Seymour Papert?

00:33:47.050 --> 00:33:49.560
We should all try harder
to learn like children

00:33:49.560 --> 00:33:52.630
is basically the point here.

00:33:52.630 --> 00:33:54.374
Papert had such an
influence for us,

00:33:54.374 --> 00:33:56.290
though, because he was
one of the first people

00:33:56.290 --> 00:33:59.260
to see computers not as these
things that have generally

00:33:59.260 --> 00:34:01.080
characterized people's
understanding--

00:34:01.080 --> 00:34:03.190
these big information
stores that

00:34:03.190 --> 00:34:04.940
are good at doing
repetitive tasks,

00:34:04.940 --> 00:34:08.560
sort of like the logical
extension of an encyclopedia.

00:34:08.560 --> 00:34:10.420
But he saw them as
these things that

00:34:10.420 --> 00:34:12.670
could be harnessed by
people to create things,

00:34:12.670 --> 00:34:15.580
to learn by doing,
by making new things

00:34:15.580 --> 00:34:19.610
by being able to actively
try and fail and try again.

00:34:19.610 --> 00:34:21.550
But here's the great irony.

00:34:21.550 --> 00:34:23.739
In the last 30 or so
years since Papert

00:34:23.739 --> 00:34:26.620
began to compel us to
rethink how to use technology

00:34:26.620 --> 00:34:29.020
to support human learning,
what we've actually seen

00:34:29.020 --> 00:34:32.230
is we've made much more progress
teaching computers how to learn

00:34:32.230 --> 00:34:34.284
than we have with people.

00:34:34.284 --> 00:34:35.784
So I'll give you
an example of this.

00:34:35.784 --> 00:34:38.139
Do people remember Deep Blue?

00:34:38.139 --> 00:34:39.949
Do people remember
Joel Benjamin?

00:34:39.949 --> 00:34:41.949
Does anyone remember
Joel Benjamin?

00:34:41.949 --> 00:34:43.820
Joel Benjamin was
the chess grandmaster

00:34:43.820 --> 00:34:46.179
that the Deep Blue
team worked with at IBM

00:34:46.179 --> 00:34:48.429
to actually encode Deep
Blue's game strategy.

00:34:48.429 --> 00:34:50.739
They basically extracted
as many if/then statements

00:34:50.739 --> 00:34:53.350
as they could from
Joel Benjamin's mind,

00:34:53.350 --> 00:34:55.179
and they created this
powerful computer

00:34:55.179 --> 00:34:58.080
that could do what Joel Benjamin
could do, just do it faster.

00:34:58.080 --> 00:35:02.080
And it was an amazing
achievement for AI at the time.

00:35:02.080 --> 00:35:04.980
But then last year, just
22 years later, there

00:35:04.980 --> 00:35:08.350
was AlphaGo, the computer that
defeated one of the world's

00:35:08.350 --> 00:35:10.370
great Go players.

00:35:10.370 --> 00:35:13.060
But this wasn't done by coding
a computer with like everything

00:35:13.060 --> 00:35:15.650
a human knows about
the game's strategy.

00:35:15.650 --> 00:35:17.740
This was done by
programming a computer

00:35:17.740 --> 00:35:20.260
to learn about how to
learn about what a good Go

00:35:20.260 --> 00:35:21.860
strategy might be.

00:35:21.860 --> 00:35:24.220
So instead of one really
smart Joel Benjamin,

00:35:24.220 --> 00:35:27.430
you basically have this ignorant
crowd of really good learners

00:35:27.430 --> 00:35:30.560
who just played Go all the time.

00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:32.740
And to put that in some
context, the difference

00:35:32.740 --> 00:35:34.870
between the number
of moves in chess

00:35:34.870 --> 00:35:37.420
and the number of moves
in Go is the difference

00:35:37.420 --> 00:35:39.730
between the number
of atoms in your body

00:35:39.730 --> 00:35:42.160
and the number of
atoms in the universe.

00:35:42.160 --> 00:35:45.850
And that in like 20 years.

00:35:45.850 --> 00:35:48.550
So what happened that allowed
for such dramatic progress

00:35:48.550 --> 00:35:49.900
in such a short time?

00:35:49.900 --> 00:35:54.370
How is that milestone of
artificial intelligence that

00:35:54.370 --> 00:35:57.010
was achieved just 20 years
ago sort of cute in comparison

00:35:57.010 --> 00:35:58.720
to what we can do today?

00:35:58.720 --> 00:36:00.550
Well, it turns out
that programming

00:36:00.550 --> 00:36:02.500
a computer to be
smart is actually

00:36:02.500 --> 00:36:07.840
much harder than programming
it to learn to be smart.

00:36:07.840 --> 00:36:09.730
Put another way,
artificial intelligence

00:36:09.730 --> 00:36:11.350
grew into machine learning.

00:36:11.350 --> 00:36:14.569
So instead of jamming computers
full of if/then statements,

00:36:14.569 --> 00:36:16.360
we give them the ability
and some structure

00:36:16.360 --> 00:36:19.360
to observe success or
progress, let them try and fail

00:36:19.360 --> 00:36:20.710
and try again.

00:36:20.710 --> 00:36:23.440
We gave them the same gift
of learning that we're all

00:36:23.440 --> 00:36:24.910
born with as children--

00:36:24.910 --> 00:36:27.250
the same gift that leads
Brandon's youngest kid

00:36:27.250 --> 00:36:30.370
to eat his sock.

00:36:30.370 --> 00:36:31.970
So what do I take
away from this?

00:36:31.970 --> 00:36:34.990
So much of traditional education
and its accompanying technology

00:36:34.990 --> 00:36:37.660
tries to give kids
that old notion

00:36:37.660 --> 00:36:38.999
of artificial intelligence.

00:36:38.999 --> 00:36:40.540
Think about all of
the facts you were

00:36:40.540 --> 00:36:43.210
asked to memorize, all the
standardized bubble tests

00:36:43.210 --> 00:36:46.480
you took, all the times the
solution was presented to you

00:36:46.480 --> 00:36:50.240
as choosing the right
if/then statement.

00:36:50.240 --> 00:36:53.740
So if it took giving
computers the technology

00:36:53.740 --> 00:36:57.272
to experientially learn at
scale to make them capable

00:36:57.272 --> 00:36:59.230
of tackling these
cosmically-hard problems like

00:36:59.230 --> 00:37:02.200
Go, then I think it should make
us realize that the technology

00:37:02.200 --> 00:37:05.320
we need to be giving humans
to help them learn needs to be

00:37:05.320 --> 00:37:08.610
focused on helping them
learn by experiencing--

00:37:08.610 --> 00:37:13.660
by having agency, not just by
giving them a bunch of facts.

00:37:13.660 --> 00:37:16.540
And that's exactly
why the emergence

00:37:16.540 --> 00:37:19.300
of widely available and
powerful, immersive computing

00:37:19.300 --> 00:37:24.830
like VR and AR is such
an exciting opportunity.

00:37:24.830 --> 00:37:28.130
It can enable the right kind
of learning moments at scale,

00:37:28.130 --> 00:37:31.040
provide people trying to learn
something with experiences,

00:37:31.040 --> 00:37:34.070
with curiosity, with
wonder, with trial and error

00:37:34.070 --> 00:37:36.020
that can be arrived
at quickly and safely.

00:37:39.250 --> 00:37:40.940
And they can inspire kids.

00:37:40.940 --> 00:37:42.850
And that's a much
more powerful force

00:37:42.850 --> 00:37:46.520
than any educational technology
that we could actually create.

00:37:46.520 --> 00:37:49.360
So if we-- and that
includes all of you--

00:37:49.360 --> 00:37:51.190
if we get this right,
we have a chance

00:37:51.190 --> 00:37:53.680
to give the same gift
that we spent the last 20

00:37:53.680 --> 00:37:58.330
years giving to rack-mounted
servers to our own students.

00:37:58.330 --> 00:38:00.940
So that's why we're really
excited to see what we all do.

00:38:00.940 --> 00:38:03.400
So thanks very much.

